# Using dangerouslySetInnerHTML in a React application
created: 2024-09-13, last updated: 2026-06-11, [Read more](https://blog.logrocket.com/using-dangerouslysetinnerhtml-react-application/)

`dangerouslySetInnerHTML` is React’s replacement for using `innerHTML`.
`dangerouslySetInnerHTML` is a property that you can use on HTML elements in a React application to programmatically set their content.
Instead of using a selector to grab the HTML element and then setting its `innerHTML`, you can use this property directly on the element.
...
## When to use dangerouslySetInnerHTMLIn**When you need to populate a `<div>` element with data coming from a rich text editor.**
Imagine you have a webpage where people can submit comments using a rich text editor.
...
…
```
const App = () => {
const data = 'lorem <b>ipsum</b>';
return (
<div>
{data}
</div>
);
}
export default App;
```
…
Note that it should be an object with the `__html` key passed to `dangerouslySetInnerHTML`.
Additionally, the element on which you use the `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` property shouldn’t have any children, hence the use of the `<div>` element as a self-closing tag.

